a now has choices for a man in her life.\n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = Ice Cream for Breakfast\n |DirectedBy      = Beth McCarthy-Miller\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Chuck Lorre & Al Higgins|t= Dave Goetsch & Matt Ross & Gina Yashere}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|9}}\n |ProdCode        = T12.16510\n |Viewers         = 5.99<ref name=\"1.10\">{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/monday-final-ratings-december-9-2019/|title='The Voice' adjusts up, 'Making It' adjusts down: Monday final ratings|last=Rejent|first=Joseph|work=TV by the Numbers|date=December 10, 2019|accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    = Frustrated with Bob, Abishola goes on a dinner date with Chukwuemeka, but finds him to be more arrogant than ever. Pushed by Tunde, Bob interrupts their date to make a passionate pitch to Abishola. Meanwhile, Dottie seems to enjoy having Tunde at the house, but she decides to convince Olu that she's lucky to have her husband in her life.\n\n''Absent'': Travis Wolfe Jr. as Dele and [[Vernee Watson]] as Gloria\n''Title quotation from'': Bob, using a simile to tell Abishola that even though their relationship doesn't make sense, it still could be something good.\n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 11\n |Title           = Splitting the Hairs\n |DirectedBy      = Beth McCarthy-Miller\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Chuck Lorre & Al Higgins & Gloria Bigelow|t= Carla Filisha & Ibet Inyang & Marla DuMont}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|16}}\n |ProdCode        = T12.16511\n |Viewers         = 6.15<ref name=\"1.11\">{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/bob-hearts-abishola-the-voice-the-great-christmas-light-fight-and-holidays-with-the-houghs-adjust-down-monday-final-ratings/|title='Bob Hearts Abishola,' 'The Voice,' 'The Great Christmas Light Fight,' and 'Holidays with the Houghs' adjust down: Monday final ratings|last=Welch|first=Alex|work=TV by the Numbers|date=December 18, 2019|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    = When Abishola insists to her friends that she wants to pursue Bob, Kemi asks Chukwuemeka for a date without telling Abishola. Abishola says it would be uncomfortable to have her best friend dating the man she is dumping, but Kemi goes on the date anyway. Kemi also finds Chukwuemeka to be boring and arrogant, leading her to ask Abishola for forgiveness. Elsewhere, Bob learns from the family lawyer that Dottie has not prepared a will, and that the business could be greatly affected if she passes away. Dottie agrees to make a will, while using the opportunity to bribe all three of her children into improving themselves. Bob and Abishola inadvertently have their first kiss.\n\n''Absent'': [[Shola Adewusi]] as Olu, [[Barry Shabaka Henley]] as Tunde, Travis Wolfe Jr. as Dele, Bayo Akinfemi as Goodwin and [[Tony Okungbowa|Anthony Okungbowa]] as Kofo\n''Title quotation from'': Kemi, debating whether she lied to Abishola or was just \"slow to tell the truth\".\n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 12\n |Title           = There's My Nigerians\n |DirectedBy      = Beth McCarthy-Miller\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Chuck Lorre & Al Higgins & Gina Yashere|t= Dave Goetsch & Carla Filisha & Matt Ross}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|6}}\n |ProdCode        = T12.16512\n |Viewers         = 6.66<ref name=\"1.12\">{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/monday-final-ratings-jan-6-2020/|title='The Bachelor' adjusts up: Monday final ratings|last=Welch|first=Alex|work=TV by the Numbers|date=January 7, 2020|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    = When Abishola suggests that Dottie is getting depressed staying in her room, Bob arranges to have two friends from Dottie's club, Jen ([[Wendie Malick]]) and Trish ([[Marilu Henner]]), pay a visit. When that backfires, Olu and Tunde make a visit. Dottie decides to get out of the house and go to her club with Olu and Tunde. This leads to a discussion about Bob and Abishola's possible marriage, wherein Dottie angers her guests by mentioning the need for a [[Prenuptial agreement|prenup]]. Meanwhile, Chukwuemeka gives Kemi a necklace after a night of sex, but he returns the next day and wants it back.\n\n''Absent'': Bayo Akinfemi as Goodwin and [[Tony Okungbowa|Anthony Okungbowa]] as Kofo\n''Title quotation from'': Dottie, when she hears Tunde and Olu pull up to take her to the club.\n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 13\n |Title           = The Canadians of Africa\n |DirectedBy      = Beth McCarthy-Miller\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Chuck Lorre & Al Higgins & Gina Yashere|t= Dave Goetsch & Carla Filisha & Matt Ross}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|20}}\n |ProdCode        = T12.16513\n |Viewers         = 6.50<ref name=\"1.13\">{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/monday-final-ratings-jan-20-2020/|title='The Neighborhood' and '9-1-1: Lone Star' adjust up: Monday final ratings|last=Welch|first=Alex|work=TV by the Numbers|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    = After noticing that Dele seems unhappy, Bob brings it up with Abishola during a dinner date and ruins their night. Later, Dele proves Bob right by telling him he wants to be a choreographer, while his mother is dead-set on him becoming a doctor. Meanwhile, Kemi tries to navigate passionate nights with Chukwuemeka when his live-in mother is always in the next room.\n\n''Title quotation from'': Kofo, describing women from [[Ghana]] after he and Goodwin suggest Bob will have to move on from Abishola.\n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 14\n |Title           = Full-Frontal Dottie \n |DirectedBy      = Beth McCarthy-Miller\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=C