ut she does not return his \"I love you\" due to cultural customs regarding showing affection. Abishola later tells Bob she is very committed to their relationship. Meanwhile, Goodwin tries to keep Kofo from riding his motor scooter, having promised relatives he would keep his younger cousin safe. Their dispute ends up in Douglas's office.\n\n''Absent'': Travis Wolfe Jr. as Dele\n''Title quotation from'': Kofo and Goodwin, telling Bob and Douglas about Michigan driving hazards that don't exist in Nigeria.\n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 16\n |Title           = Where's Your Other Wives, Tunde?\n |DirectedBy      =  Beth McCarthy-Miller\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Chuck Lorre|t=Al Higgins}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|17}}\n |ProdCode        = T12.16516\n |Viewers         = 6.12<ref name=\"1.16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-monday-cable-originals-network-finals-2-17-2020.html|title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Monday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 2.17.2020|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|date=February 19, 2020|work=Showbuzz Daily|accessdate= February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    = As Dottie mends fences with Olu and Tunde, Bob professes to the three of them that he and Abishola don't have a \"real\" relationship yet. An angry Abishola asks Bob to explain, and he later tells her that, among other things, they haven't had sexual relations. Abishola responds by saying that she has never had sex outside of marriage. After Bob sulks and drinks all day, Abishola calls him late at night to say she isn't ruling out the possibility of intimacy in the near future.\n\n''Title quotation from'': Dottie, asking Olu and Tunde about polygamy in Nigeria.\n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 17\n |Title           = A Big, White Thumb\n |DirectedBy      = Beth McCarthy-Miller\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Chuck Lorre & Gina Yashere & Carla Filisha|t=Matt Ross}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|9}}\n |ProdCode        = T12.16517\n |Viewers         = 5.81<ref name=\"1.17\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-monday-cable-originals-network-finals-3-9-2020.html|title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Monday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 3.9.2020|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|date=March 10, 2020|work=Showbuzz Daily|accessdate= March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    =  During a dinner with her family, Abishola invites Bob to church. Bob is a little reluctant and inadvertently offends Abishola while trying to explain his nonreligiousness, but eventually agrees to do so to make amends. After an uncomfortable experience during the church service, Abishola wonders how their relationship will ever last. Bob tells her that even though he might not believe in God, he believes in miracles, citing the two of them as an example.\n\n''Absent'': Bayo Akinfemi as Goodwin and [[Tony Okungbowa|Anthony Okungbowa]] as Kofo\n''Title quotation from'': Tunde, extrapolating on Abishola's reluctance to invite Bob to church.\n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 18\n |Title           = Sock Wife!\n |DirectedBy      = Beth McCarthy-Miller\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Chuck Lorre & Al Higgins & Gloria Bigelow|t=Matt Ross & Dave Goetsch & Gina Yashere}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|16}}\n |ProdCode        = T12.16518\n |Viewers         = 6.89<ref name=\"1.18\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-monday-cable-originals-network-finals-3-16-2020.html|title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Monday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 3.16.2020|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|date=March 17, 2020|work=Showbuzz Daily|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    =  After discovering from Kemi that Bob's ex-wife Lorraine ([[Nicole Sullivan]]) has been admitted to the hospital, Abishola makes a visit to the woman's room. With Abishola's help, Bob prays for his ex-wife's happiness and slowly begins to let go of some of his animosity towards her. The exes share a hug that Kemi witnesses, and Abishola grows concerned that Lorraine still has feelings for Bob. Meanwhile, Christina recruits Kofo to help with online branding, and the two find themselves drawn to one another.\n\n''Absent'': [[Christine Ebersole]] as Dottie and Travis Wolfe Jr. as Dele\n''Title quotation from'': Kemi, out of breath from running and trying to explain Lorraine's presence in the hospital to Abishola.\n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 19\n |Title           = Angry, Happy, Same Face\n |DirectedBy      = Beth McCarthy-Miller\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Chuck Lorre & Gina Yashere & Ibet Inyang|t=Matt Ross & Carla Filisha & Marla DuMont}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|06}}\n |ProdCode        = T12.16519\n |Viewers         = \n |ShortSummary    = When Bob's ex-wife Lorraine shows up at Bob's house several days in a row, and even reconciles with Dottie, Abishola begins to take exception. Meanwhile, Christina continues to pursue Kofo, who is reluctant to accept her offers of a date because he fears losing his job if the relationship ends badly. This forces Douglas and Bob to take drastic measures.\n\n''Absent'': Travis Wolfe Jr. as Dele\n''Title quotation from'': Kemi, explaining to Gloria how difficult it is to decipher Abishola's emotions.\n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 20\n |Title           = Randy's a Wrangler\n |RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|title=(#BHA120) \"Randy's a Wrangler\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200402cbs03/|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n |DirectedBy      = Beth McCarthy-Miller\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Chuck Lorre & Al Higgins & Gina Yashere|t=Matt Ross & Dave Goetsch & Carla Filisha}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|13}}\n |ProdCode        = \n |Viewers         = \n |ShortSummary    =  <!-- Episode summaries must be expressed in your own words. Do NOT submit content you find from another web site as it is plagiarism and likely a copyright violation, which Wikipedia cannot accept and will be removed or reverted. Superficially modifying copyrighted content or closely paraphrasing it, even if the source is cited, still constitutes a copyright violation. Summaries should be about 100 to 200 words in length, per MOS:TVPLOT, and those substantially less than 100 words are most likely to be scrutinized for possible copyright violation. -->\n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn October 5, 2018, it was announced that CBS had given the production an early pilot order. The pilot was written by [[Chuck Lorre]], who executive produced along with [[Eddie Gorodetsky]], [[Al Higgins]] and [[Gina Yashere]].<ref name=\"deadline 1\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/chuck-lorre-bob-hearts-abishola-comedy-billy-gardell-star-cbs-series-gina-yashere-eddie-gorodetsky-al-higgins-1202477359/|title=Chuck Lorre Comedy 'Bob \u2661's Abishola' Starring Billy Gardell Set At CBS With Pilot Production Commitment|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> Production companies involved with the pilot included Chuck Lorre Productions and [[Warner Bros. Television]]. On May 6, 2019, it was announced that the production had been given a series order.<ref name=\"deadline 2\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/cbs-orders-comedy-series-bob-hearts-abishola-broke-carols-second-act-the-unicorn-1202611317/|title=CBS Orders Comedy Series 'Bob \u2661 Abishola', 'Broke', 'Carol's Second Act' & 'The Unicorn'|work=Deadline Hollywood|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=May 9, 2019|access-date=May 10, 2019}}</ref> A day after that, it was announced that the series would premiere in the fall of 2019 and air on Mondays at 8:30&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"Fall2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/cbs-fall-2019-20-schedule-new-shows-upfronts-pauley-perrette-mike-colter-chuck-lorre-simone-missick-1202615155/|title=CBS Fall 2019\u201320 Schedule: Some Diverse Moves for the Most-Watched Network, But Lots of Familiar Faces|work=Deadline Hollywood|last=Patten|first=Dominic|date=May 15, 2019|access-date=May 16, 2019}}</ref> The series debuted on September 23, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/cbs-fall-premiere-dates-bob-hearts-abishola-all-rise-evil-young-sheldon-ncis-blue-bloods-madam-secretary-1202632379/|title=CBS Sets Fall Premiere Dates: 'Bob \u2665 Abishola', 'All Rise', 'Evil', 'Young Sheldon', 'NCIS', 'Blue Bloods' & More|work=Deadline Hollywood|first1=Denise|last1=Petski|first2=Nellie|last2=Andreeva|date=June 13, 2019|accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref> On October 22, 2019, it was announced that CBS had ordered an additional nine episodes of the series.<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |title=\u2018Evil\u2019 Renewed For Season 2 By CBS; \u2018All Rise\u2019, \u2018Carol\u2019s Second Act\u2019, \u2018The Unicorn\u2019 & \u2018Bob \u2665 Abishola\u2019 Get Back Orders |url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/evil-renewed-season-2-cbs-all-rise-carols-second-act-the-unicorn-bob-%e2%99%a5-abishola-back-orders-full-season-1202766547/|website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=October 23, 2019 |date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> On March 13, 2020, Warner Bros. Television has suspended the production following the [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television|impact of corona-virus]] pandemic.<Ref>https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-tv-shows-production-delayed-1202881997/</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nOn December 17, 2018, it was announced that five co-leads, opposite [[Billy Gardell]] and [[Folake Olowofoyeku]] as the title characters, had been cast, including [[Christine Ebersole]], [[Maribeth Monroe]], [[Matt Jones (actor)|Matt Jones]], [[Shola Adewusi]] and [[Barry Shabaka Henley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/bob-hearts-abishola-folake-olowofoyeku-christine-ebersole-maribeth-monroe-six-cast-chuck-lorre-comedy-1202521435/|title='Bob Hearts Abishola': Folake Olowofoyeku, Christine Ebersole, Maribeth Monroe Among Six Cast In Chuck Lorre Comedy|last=Petski|first=Denise|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=December 17, 2018|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis is Gardell's second starring role in a CBS sitcom, after ''[[Mike & Molly]]'', which ran from 2010 to 2016 and was also executive produced by Lorre; in addition, Gardell has a recurring role on ''[[Young Sheldon]]'' as Herschel Sparks, a neighbor of the title character. Matt Jones is an alum of fellow Lorre/CBS series ''[[Mom (TV series)|Mom]]''. On January 30, 2020, it was reported that [[Tony Okungbowa|Anthony Okungbowa]] and Bayo Akinfemi have been promoted  as a series regulars.<ref name=\"AO&BASeriesRegulars\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/bob-hearts-abishola-ups-anthony-okungbowa-bayo-akinfemi-to-series-regulars-1202846206/|title='Bob \u2665 Abishola' Ups Anthony Okungbowa & Bayo Akinfemi To Series Regulars|last=Petski|first=Denise|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=January 30, 2020|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Marketing===\nOn May 15, 2019, CBS released the first official trailer for the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=CBS New Series Trailers: 'Bob Hearts Abishola', 'Carol's Second Act', 'Evil', 'All Rise', 'FBI: Most Wanted', More|url=https://deadline.com/video/cbs-new-series-trailers-bob-hearts-abishola-carols-second-act-evil-all-rise-fbi-most-wanted-tommy-the-unicorn-broke/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=May 15, 2019|date=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nThe [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported a 58% approval rating with an average rating of 6.75/10, based on 12 reviews. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Groundbreaking, but unfortunately grating, ''Bob (Hearts) Abishola'' undermines its own progressive premise with underwhelming humor that relies too heavily on outdated stereotypes.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/bob_hearts_abishola/s01|title=''Bob (Hearts) Abishola'': Season 1 |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] ([[Fandango Media]]) |accessdate=September 27, 2019}}</ref> Metacritic, which uses a weighted average, assigned a score of 57 out of 100 based on 10 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/bob-hearts-abishola/season-1|title=Bob Hearts Abishola: Season 1|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n{{Television episode ratings\n| width     = 99\n\n| title1    = [[#ep1|Pilot]]\n| date1     = September 23, 2019\n| rs1       = 0.9/4\n| viewers1  = 5.89<ref name=\"1.01\"/>\n| dvr1      = 0.3\n| dvrv1     = 1.56\n| total1    = 1.2\n| totalv1   = 7.45<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/stumptown-evil-emergence-top-7-day-ratings-gains-new-shows-1246200|title=TV Ratings: Where New Series Stand in First 7-Day Numbers|last=Porter|first=Rick|date=October 8, 2019|work=Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n| title2    = [[#ep2|Nigerians Don't Do Useless Things]]\n| date2     = September 30, 2019\n| rs2       = 0.7/3\n| viewers2  = 5.36<ref name=\"1.02\"/>\n| dvr2      = 0.2\n| dvrv2     = 1.50\n| total2    = 0.9\n| totalv2   = 6.87<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/live7-ratings-week-of-sept-30-evil-stumptown-emergence-1203371610/|title=Live+7 Ratings for Week of Sept. 30: 'Evil,' 'Stumptown,' and 'Emergence' All Double|last=Thorne|first=Will|date=October 15, 2019|work=Variety|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n| title3    = [[#ep3|A Bird May Love A Fish]]\n| date3     = October 7, 2019\n| rs3       = 0.7/3\n| viewers3  = 5.30<ref name=\"1.03\"/>\n| dvr3      = 0.3\n| dvrv3     = 1.44\n| 